For this homework, Bullion Gold Selling Price (TRY/Gr),(USD) US Dollar (Selling), and Domestic Debt Position (Treasury)(TRY Thousand)(Monthly) data were retrieved from Central Bank of the Republic of Turkey (CBRT) and three search cases corresponding these data sets were retrieved by using Google Trends. After having received these, ultimate aim is to evaluate both google trends data and Central Bank data both by individually, dual matchings and altogether and then come up with an analysis of their relationships: distributions, trends, correlation.

Following code is to install and call relevant packages to perform analysis well by using visualization tools. gold_usd_debt data was extracted from TCMB and only relevant rows were used. Tarih coloumn was transformed as year format to perform the code and other coloumns related to gold and USD exchange rate were formatted as numeric rather than char. Output of this code is the main attributes of the data and used to check its validity to run the code in a correct way.

1. Bullion Gold Selling Price (TRY/Gr) data from TCMB & ‘Gram Altın’ search volume from Google Trends

Bullion Gold Selling Price (TRY/Gr) data shows the TRY value of one gram of gold from April 2017 to February 2022.

Corresponding Line Graph and its smoothed line:

ggplot(data=gold_usd_debt)+
  labs(title = "Bullion Gold Selling Price (TRY/Gr)", x = "Time", y = "Levels" ) +
  geom_line(group=1,size=1,color='blue', aes(x=Tarih,y=`TP MK KUL YTL`)) +
  geom_smooth(fill = NA, color="green",linetype = "twodash", size = 0.7, aes(x=Tarih,y=`TP MK KUL YTL`))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

Line graph of gold data shows that there is an increasing trend and also the slope of this trend is increasing, meaning that either gold gains more value than try or vice versa (“learning by living” is the source of the deduction that TRY’s losing its value against other currencies and gold.) There are two time intervals that the TRY/Gr has decreased: The first one was started by the end of 2021 and continued until February 2022. The second decreasing trend occured starting from approximately mids of 2022 and lasted during the summer season. These two occurences migth be because of some initiatives taken intentionally decrease the level of gold-TRY comparison. However, this decreasing trend did not last long enough and followed by a sharp increase starting from the third quarter of 2021.

Histogram of Gold-TRY data to have a better understanding of the trend and change frequencies:

ggplot(data = gold_usd_debt,aes(x = `TP MK KUL YTL` )) +
  geom_histogram(bins=15,alpha=0.6,aes(color=Year,fill=Year))+
  facet_wrap(facets= .~Year)+
  scale_color_brewer(palette = "Paired",aesthetics = c("color", "fill")) +
  labs(title = "Histograms of Gold Selling Price",
       x = "Gold Selling Price",
       y = "Frequency")

This histogram shows the frequencies of Gold Selling for each year and the increasing trend can be seen from here as well. We can conclude from this histograms that the steady state of Gold Selling Price was lost by the time passed since we have, in general, more price intervals and less corresponding frequency values from 2017 to 2021, which means the Gold Selling Price started to change more rapidly and the change is now more obvious than before.

Boxplot of Gold-TRY data to examine the trend and standard deviation of the values:

ggplot(data = gold_usd_debt,aes(x=factor(Year),y=`TP MK KUL YTL`))+ 
  geom_boxplot(aes(fill=factor(Year)))+ 
  xlab("Years") + ylab("Gold Selling Price")+ 
  ggtitle("Boxplot for Gold Selling Price")+
  theme(legend.position = "none")

From the boxplot showing the results in yearly-grouped manner, we can deduce the already-seen increasing trend along with the standard deviation behaviour, which was largest for 2022 since having the widest box width. In addition, we can see that there are two outliers in the boxplot for 2021.

Search volume of “gram altın”:

gram_altin <- read_excel("/Users/ertugruluyar/Downloads/gram-altin.xlsx")
gram_altin$tariha <- as.yearmon(x = gram_altin$tariha)
ggplot(data = gram_altin)+
  geom_point(group =1,size = 1, color ='purple', aes(x=tariha, y= counta))+
  geom_smooth(fill = NA, color="orange",linetype = "twodash", size = 0.7, aes(x=tariha,y= counta))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

“gram altın” search is important because people try to evaluate the economic situation and make investments. This phrase reflects the aim of people trying to understand what is going on with TRY compared to gold. From the scatter plot, we can see the similar trend as in the line graph of the data from TCMB. The largest value points in this graphs correspond to where we see the pick points of Gold Selling Price (after the midst of 2018, 2021 and during the midst of 2022), which is highly reasonable. It can also be deduced that the search volume is not only correlated with the value of gold but also the speed of change of the value of gold.

2. (USD) US Dollar (Selling) data from TCMB & ‘Dolar Kuru’ search volume from Google Trends

(USD) US Dollar (Selling data shows the exchange rate between USD and TRY from April 2017 to February 2022.

Corresponding Line Graph and its smoothed line:

ggplot(data=gold_usd_debt)+
  labs(title = "(USD) US Dollar (Selling)", x = "Time", y = "Levels" ) +
  geom_line(group=1,size=1,color='red', aes(x=Tarih,y=`TP DK USD S YTL`)) +
  geom_smooth(fill = NA, color="magenta",linetype = "twodash", size = 0.7, aes(x=Tarih,y=`TP DK USD S YTL`))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

With some ups and downs in the short term, the overall data has an increasing trend in an accelerated fashion, which can be seen from the smoothed line of the line graph. The two most acceleration are seen after the second quarter of 2018 and the third quarter of 2021.

Histogram of USD-TRY data to have a better understanding of the trend and change frequencies:

ggplot(data = gold_usd_debt,aes(x =`TP DK USD S YTL` )) +
  geom_histogram(bins=15,alpha=0.6,aes(color=Year,fill=Year))+
  facet_wrap(facets= .~Year)+
  scale_color_brewer(palette = "Paired",aesthetics = c("color", "fill")) +
  labs(title = "Histograms of US Dollar-TRY",
       x = "USD-TRY",
       y = "Frequency")

The increasing trend can also be seen from these histograms since the x-value densities were moved from left to right. In addition, we can say that there are more rapid changes in 2018, 2020, and 2021 compared to 2017 and 2019 since former ones had more intervals of x values, showing the variability.

Boxplot of USD-TRY data to examine the trend and standard deviation of the values:

ggplot(data = gold_usd_debt,aes(x=factor(Year),y=`TP DK USD S YTL`))+ 
  geom_boxplot(aes(fill=factor(Year)))+ 
  xlab("Years") + ylab("US Dollar-TRY")+ 
  ggtitle("Boxplot for US Dollar-TRY")+
  theme(legend.position = "none")

We can see the beloved increasing trend here also and moreover, by evaluating the widths of the boxes, we can infer that the standard deviation is high for 2018, 2020 and 2022, respectively. Furthermore, there are also two outlier data in 2021.

Search volume of “doviz kuru”:

I chose “doviz kuru” as the possible phrase that can be relevant to the USD-TRY data because people concerned about the economic situation and their investments are likely to search this phrase. From this scatter plot and its smoothed line, we can see that there are some points that are higher in volume where we have percentage change larger than before in our data from TCMB, meaning that the speed of the change is important for the people to search for this phenomena. 3. Domestic Debt Position (Treasury)(TRY Thousand)(Monthly) data from TCMB & ‘Türkiye Borç’ search volume from Google Trends

Domestic Debt Position (Treasury)(TRY Thousand)(Monthly) data shows domestic debt situation regarding treasury of Turkey from April 2017 to February 2022.

Corresponding Line Graph and its smoothed line:

ggplot(data=gold_usd_debt)+
  labs(title = "Domestic Debt Position (Treasury)(TRY Thousand)(Monthly)", x = "Time", y = "Levels" ) +
  geom_line(group=1,size=1,color='purple', aes(x=Tarih,y=`TP KB A09`))+
  geom_smooth(fill = NA, color="red",linetype = "twodash", size = 0.7, aes(x=Tarih,y=`TP KB A09`))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

The domestic debt data shows an inreasing trend with an acceleration started approximately from the third quarter of 2019 and lasted nearly nine months. AFter having a slight decrease compared to the speed of the increase, this increase continues with less acceleration.

Histogram of Domestic Debt Position data to have a better understanding of the trend and change frequencies:

ggplot(data = gold_usd_debt,aes(x =`TP KB A09` )) +
  geom_histogram(bins=15,alpha=0.6,aes(color=Year,fill=Year))+
  facet_wrap(facets= .~Year)+
  scale_color_brewer(palette = "Paired",aesthetics = c("color", "fill")) +
  labs(title = "Histograms of Domestic Debt Position",
       x = "Domestic Debt Position",
       y = "Frequency")

These histograms shows the increase in domestic debt position deduced from the intensity of data’s in x-axis moving from left to right and the variability of the debt position by the data’s distribution intervals, which illustrates the rapid changes started from 2019 to 2021.

Boxplot of Domestic Debt Position data to examine the trend and standard deviation of the values:

ggplot(data = gold_usd_debt,aes(x=factor(Year),y=`TP KB A09`))+ 
  geom_boxplot(aes(fill=factor(Year)))+ 
  xlab("Years") + ylab("Domestic Debt Position")+ 
  ggtitle("Boxplot for Domestic Debt Position")+
  theme(legend.position = "none")

We can infer from the boxplots that the Domestic Debt regarding to Turkey’s treasury has more standart deviation in 2020, which has the constant rapid changes all year long. Moreover, we can see the maximum value of domestic debt from the upper whisker of the 2022’s boxplot. In addition, there occured an outlier in 2021.

Search volume of “Türkiye Borç”:

borc <- read_excel("/Users/ertugruluyar/Downloads/borc.xlsx")

## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

By looking at the scatter plot of the search volume of “Türkiye Borç” phrase and its smoothed line, I was expect to the similar trend however there is no obvious correlation between the debt position and the phrase. This may be due to people’s being less aware of the economical factors that are not usually spoken in public’s view. One thing that immediately catches the is the region between 2019 and 2019, where see the most frequent searches of the phrase; however, we cannot make any conclusions about this trend by just looking at the graphs and there may need to have a political or sociological explanation of this behaviour.

Comparing 3 Data Sets and Their Corresponding Phrases’ Search Volumes

To examine the correlations between each pair of Gold-USD-Debt data:

plot(gold_usd_debt)

From the plot, we can see the obvious relations which are almost linear and have high positive correlations between them, meaning that they all follow the similar patterns and may have similar economic and political causes.

Commonalities of this three subsets of data (gold, USD, debt) and their related phrases’ search volumes:

-They all have increasing trend in an accelerated fashion. (from line graphs, histograms and boxplots) -They all have more variability by the time passes (from histograms and boxplots) -They all have outliers in 2021. -Gold and USD have similar trend in search volumes and that volumes responded the speed of change of the value of Gold/USD compared to TRY, while Domestic Debt’s corresponding phrase did not respond to the change as what I expected.
